Fragmentary World
The World Is Flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman says this. Friedman chose this provocative book title for his bestseller to make people aware of the astonishing impact of technology on the global economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide protection.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States all have to face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they talk to may very well be far away in India.
Skeptics point out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but "uneven."
The contour map of global economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of poverty.
Not only that, distance has far from lost its significance.
Even between neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, domestic trade far exceeds cross-border trade.
Although Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, Vancouver's trade with the farther Toronto is much higher than with the nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as mutual dependence between different continents, its history is as long as human history, witnessing migration of races and religions, as well as the ancient trade along the Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is developing faster and more deeply.
In 1868, after the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid, Europe and the United States could communicate within a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described how a British person living in London could order goods from around the world by telephone and then sit at home waiting for them to arrive in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British person was an exception, someone wealthy enough to afford such convenience.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world in local supermarkets.
Similarly, twenty years ago there was instant global communication, but it was beyond the financial reach of most people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet café and gain access to capabilities that were once only available to governments, multinational corporations, and a small number of individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant reduction in the costs of computation, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly widespread.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, the proportion of internet users in the United States accounts for less than a quarter of the global total.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached an all-time high in human history.
Non-state institutions now possess capabilities that were once exclusively controlled by governments.
The position of the nation-state as a key actor in world politics will not change for now, but it must learn to share this vast stage with more participants, including institutions like the Oxford Centre for Global Health Ethics, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
However, this process of flattening is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
In 1914, the world economy was highly integrated, but over the next 30 years, economic interdependence among countries continuously declined.
It wasn't until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had previously known, and even then, it was still constrained by the heavy barriers of the Iron Curtain.
World War I was the catalyst for this reversal, and during the two World Wars and the one global Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflected deeper issues caused by 19th-century economic development, such as domestic inequality.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—flourishing at the expense of national and global unity.
After World War II, the welfare state system in the West created a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits of international economic interdependence.
Some analysts argue that China's role today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly developing in the direction of nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and ultimately triggering world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, were the economies of Britain and Germany before 1914 not also highly interdependent?
But this reasoning is incomplete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had already surpassed that of Britain.
But even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with the United States within at least 20 years.
The greater threat to the flat world may come from non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in an unannounced attack than the Japanese government's attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such forces were to acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo radical changes.
At that time, the movement of people and goods across borders would become more difficult.
If these forces were to disrupt the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic depression similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effects of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the lead in promoting policies to eliminate obstacles.
But the events described above may reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization may welcome such an outcome.
However, such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situations in two areas—namely, the reversal of the trend of economic globalization that spreads technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization further consolidate, such as war, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If this is the case, the flat world would become a desert.
